			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Should start shortly, hopefully my computer has enough juice.</p>
<p>Panel is hosted by Cyrus Krohn, RNC e-Campaign Director.<span id="more-3586"></span></p>
<p>Party is further along technologically than the press would have us believe.</p>
<p>Krohn is from Fairfax. Nice.</p>
<p>Obama captured 13 million emails. RNC and McCain possessed 12 million emails (about 6 million each).  Almost parity (though no word what DNC&#8217;s list has).</p>
<p>Host 30 state party websites with email platform, they provide those emails to the party for free and website hosing services for free. Seeking to provide applications to parties that aren&#8217;t on their service to gain access to their database.</p>
<p>Now he&#8217;s talking about the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Long_Tail">Long Tail</a>. Long tail represents internet and new blogs. Easier to use to communicate as it&#8217;s easier to find them, harder before they&#8217;re scattered.</p>
<p>Text &#8220;join&#8221; to 46708 to join the RNC text list.  Will contact you based on area code so MD zip gets MD updates (sorry, Krystal).  Eventually may narrow to zip code (vendor issue).</p>
<p>Communication: online presence to empower activists and spread message. Internet will not win elections for you, candidate will.</p>
<p>Video is a must have. Talks of finding camera for a couple hundred bucks to spread message/track. I recommend <a href="http://www.bestbuy.com/site/olspage.jsp?skuId=8480716&amp;st=flip+camera&amp;lp=1&amp;type=product&amp;cp=1&amp;id=1185268654578">$150 Flip</a> for quick and easy entry level video.</p>
<p>Obama ran a flawless online campaign. Feels we need to get online offline - capture their hearts and minds online and get them on the streets.</p>
<p>Network via FaceBook, MySpace, YouTube, Twitter, etc.  Tap into viral effect (friends inviting friends).</p>
<p>Showed how you can use Twitter to update your Facebook. Just friended him, if I was already his friend I&#8217;d have IM&#8217;d him on FB and shown it on the big screen. Ah well.</p>
<p>Questions on how you can tell if folks click links and should you get a younger crowd to set it up and run it for you.  Awkward answers.</p>
<p>Bloggers do not adhere to same journalistic standards as media. You need to be conscious of what people are saying about you.  Recommends <a href="http://blogsearch.google.com">Google Blogsearch</a>. Hasn&#8217;t hit on message control yet.</p>
<p>Cites Google Bombing, which isn&#8217;t as big as it used to be due to an algorithm shift.</p>
<p>Question on how to properly respond to bad blogs or figure out good from bad.  I ended up speaking up, find the diamonds in the rough, as time goes by the cream will rise to the top, will shift to the big head of the long tail, and you can use THOSE guys, ignore the trash, trust the diamonds.</p>
<p>Sorry for the break, I ended up going and talking to the group, I forget what I said.  My bad.</p>
<p>Shilled <a href="http://www.redstormpac.org">RedStormPAC</a>, was told by a guy in the back they weren&#8217;t here to hear me, undersood.</p>
<p>Google search ads for cheap. Which a lot of folks need to know more about - you can advertise for pennies a click. DON&#8217;T LET THE OTHER GUYS BUY YOUR NAME OR KEYWORDS - great point.  Same with domain names. Protect yourself.</p>
<p>A lot of questions on what to buy and how much to spend to protect yourself online: domains, search terms, advertisements, etc. - how to track who visits and reply to them directly.</p>
